      Goldman cloud
   =20
 =20
Much of the business of an investment bank=E2=80=99s sales and trading divi=
sion consists of calling up clients and saying =E2=80=9Chey you should do t=
his trade, this trade would be good for you.=E2=80=9D Perhaps the trade wou=
ld be good for the client. But the actual point is that it would be good fo=
r the bank; the bank would collect some commission or fee or spread or edge=
 for executing or financing the trade. If clients do lots of trades the ban=
k makes lots of money. If clients do not do trades the bank makes no money.=
This is obviously complicated and subtle and exhausting work. You have to c=
all lots of clients and suggest lots of trades, and if the suggestions are =
stupid the clients won=E2=80=99t do the trades and will stop taking your ca=
lls and do trades with some other bank. So you have to think of trades that=
 the client will like, which requires knowing a lot about the market and th=
e clients.Ideally you will do such a good job of (1) recommending good trad=
es, (2) sounding smart while you do it and (3) taking the client to sportin=
g events that the client will start calling=C2=A0you=C2=A0for trade ideas. =
Instead of you calling and saying =E2=80=9Chey you should do this trade,=E2=
=80=9D the client will call you and say =E2=80=9Chey what trades should I d=
o?=E2=80=9D You have become a trusted adviser whom the client relies on for=
 ideas, which also means that the client will execute those ideas with you =
and you=E2=80=99ll make a lot of money.Can this all be automated? Sure why =
not:Goldman Sachs is getting into the cloud computing business.The bank is =
opening up access to its trove of market data and software tools to hedge f=
unds and asset managers in an offering designed with Amazon=E2=80=99s cloud=
 division, CNBC has learned exclusively.The move, the result of a two-year =
collaboration with AWS, puts 152-year-old Goldman in the unusual position o=
f being a provider of cloud services for Wall Street, according to executiv=
es at the two firms. It=E2=80=99s part of Goldman CEO David Solomon=E2=80=
=99s push to use technology to better serve clients of the firm=E2=80=99s m=
arkets division, a trading juggernaut that has helped drive the firm=E2=80=
=99s results this year. =E2=80=A6A hedge fund client who wanted to chart th=
e correlation between a stock and currency exchange rates, for instance, co=
uld take months to assemble and clean the data and perform calculations wit=
h it, said [Goldman co-chief information officer Marco] Argenti. Instead, b=
y building applications atop data feeds and analytic tools that Goldman its=
elf uses, the analysis can be done in minutes, he said.=E2=80=9CIf this exi=
sted we would=E2=80=99ve used it, but we had to build it for ourselves beca=
use there really is nothing like this in the market,=E2=80=9D Argenti said.=
 =E2=80=9CAll you need to do is assemble the interface and integrate it wit=
h your application and then everything else is kind of taken care of for yo=
u.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6The executives declined to give details about how Gold=
man and AWS would share revenue from the joint project, but Solomon told CN=
BC that he saw it as a way to further entrench the firm with trading client=
s. Goldman plans to monetize the service through the trading and financing =
opportunities that it will generate, he said.=E2=80=9CThis is something tha=
t enhances the experience of our institutional clients and gives them acces=
s to our data and information,=E2=80=9D Solomon said. =E2=80=9CThe way we g=
et paid for that is we get more of their wallet share because the overall e=
xperience and services we provide gives us more mindshare, more opportuniti=
es to trade with them, to finance them and do things like that.=E2=80=9DIf =
you are a bank, you don=E2=80=99t want your hedge fund clients to spend mon=
ths assembling and cleaning data and performing calculations with it before=
 doing a trade!=C2=A0You want them to do trades=C2=A0today, not months from=
 now. Honestly you=E2=80=99d be fine if they did trades without analysis an=
d calculations, but in modern financial markets that=E2=80=99s a hard pitch=
; =E2=80=9Clet us help you do the analysis quickly=E2=80=9D is the best you=
 are going to do. What you want is for your clients to come to work every m=
orning and think about trade ideas using a tool with your brand name on it,=
 and also for them not to think about those ideas for too long before they =
call you to do the trade.We  talked last year about another delightful Gold=
man tech project,[1] an app that it offered to investment banking clients =
=E2=80=9Cto identify sale or=C2=A0spin-off=C2=A0opportunities and possible =
takeover targets in the form of unloved or poorly performing company divisi=
ons.=E2=80=9D That is a really good trade-idea generator to leave with the =
client: If the client fiddles around with your app and it tells her =E2=80=
=9Cyou should divest a $10 billion business=E2=80=9D and she believes it, s=
he will almost certainly call you to do the divestiture and you=E2=80=99ll =
collect an eight-digit fee for it.=E2=80=9CHey here=E2=80=99s some market d=
ata=E2=80=9D is maybe less obviously lucrative, but on the other hand it=E2=
=80=99s much more general-purpose. You don=E2=80=99t have to tell the clien=
t what trade to do. You just leave them with a machine that will help them =
generate trades and give them a general warm feeling about you.=C2=A0
