   =20
      Glencore
   =20
 =20
If you are a big investor who cares about environmental, social and governa=
nce issues, one thing that you might do is refuse to invest in companies th=
at mine thermal coal. This way, you will not have any thermal coal in your =
portfolio and you will feel good about yourself. Also if a lot of big inves=
tors refuse to invest in coal miners, that will raise the cost of capital o=
f coal miners, which will lead to less coal mining, or that is  the theory =
anyway.=C2=A0One criticism of this approach is that it actually=C2=A0reduce=
s=C2=A0the influence that ESG-minded investors have over problematic compan=
ies. If there is a company that does some coal mining, and also some good e=
nvironmental stuff, what you want is for the company to cut back on the coa=
l mining and ramp up the good stuff. If you own its stock, you can go meet =
with the managers and lobby for that approach. But if you have a bright-lin=
e rule saying =E2=80=9Cno thermal coal,=E2=80=9D who will meet with the man=
agers and lobby for that approach?I think the answer is that a group of ESG=
 activist investors have sprung up whose basic mission is =E2=80=9Clobby co=
mpanies to become more appealing to ESG investors=E2=80=9D?  Anyway:Activis=
t hedge fund Bluebell Capital Partners has asked Glencore Plc to separate i=
ts thermal coal business because it has become a barrier to investment.The =
hedge fund firm said that the commodities giant could realize more value fo=
r shareholders if it separates that business, simplifies its asset base, di=
sposes of non-core asset Viterra, and tackles governance issues. Bluebell=
=E2=80=99s partners Giuseppe Bivona and Marco Taricco made the demands in a=
 letter to the company, a copy of which was seen by Bloomberg. =E2=80=A6Lon=
don-based Bluebell, which has shaken boardrooms across Europe and launched =
activist campaigns against companies from GlaxoSmithKline Plc to Danone SA,=
 said Glencore=E2=80=99s coal activities were hurting its valuation both fr=
om a pure ESG perspective but also because of the uncertainty on terminal v=
alue. The pair said that the company=E2=80=99s plan to keep thermal coal as=
 part of its portfolio until 2050 is both =E2=80=9Cmorally unacceptable and=
 financially flawed.=E2=80=9D=E2=80=9CDue to its coal business, Glencore is=
 not an investible company for investors who place sustainability at the he=
art of their investment process,=E2=80=9D Bluebell=E2=80=99s partners wrote=
 in the letter dated Nov. 8. =E2=80=9CA clear separation between carbonised=
 and de-carbonised assets is needed to increase shareholder value and remov=
e the =E2=80=98coal discount,=E2=80=99 whilst simultaneously ensuring that =
coal assets will be managed responsibly.=E2=80=9DWe have talked before abou=
t  Engine No. 1 LLC=E2=80=99s activist campaign to make Exxon Mobil Corp. m=
ore ESG-friendly, and about  Dan Loeb=E2=80=99s campaign to make Royal Dutc=
h Shell Plc split its environmentally friendly renewables businesses off fr=
om its dirty upstream and refining businesses. There is an obvious audience=
 for this stuff. In some rough sense the audience is BlackRock Inc., the gi=
ant institutional asset manager that (1) has  announced plans not to invest=
 in thermal coal and (2) owns 8.3% of Glencore, oops. BlackRock cannot exac=
tly lobby Glencore to change its behavior by saying =E2=80=9Cdue to its coa=
l business, Glencore is not an investible company for BlackRock,=E2=80=9D b=
ecause there it is owning 8.3% of Glencore. But Bluebell can say that, thou=
gh it sensibly refers to generic =E2=80=9Cinvestors who place sustainabilit=
y at the heart of their investment process.=E2=80=9DOn the other hand, the =
criticism that we started with =E2=80=94=C2=A0that ESG investor divesting f=
rom coal actually reduces their influence =E2=80=94=C2=A0also applies to pl=
ans for public companies to get rid of coal assets:Bluebell=E2=80=99s lette=
r comes at a strange time. Executives at some of the biggest miners say tha=
t push to exit the fuel from investors is easing, amid a recognition that s=
elling or spinning off assets can lead to more coal being mined for longer.=
=C2=A0BHP Group=E2=80=99s exit from the fuel is no longer certain, while Gl=
encore itself has gone to great lengths to make its investors more comforta=
ble with its continued ownership, including capping its own production.=C2=
=A0If Glencore, a public company with=C2=A0lots of revenue from =E2=80=9Cfu=
ture facing metals such as cobalt and copper,=E2=80=9D owns coal mines, it =
will face pressure from ESG-oriented shareholders to reduce its coal mining=
 and ramp up its cleaner businesses. If it sells the coal mines to some pri=
vate company specifically looking to grab cheap coal assets from ESG-pressu=
red public companies, that private company is gonna mine all the coal as fa=
st as possible.=C2=A0One rough model that you could have for modern corpora=
te finance is that most senior corporate executives are mostly in the busin=
ess of maximizing cash flows for shareholders, because that is what they we=
re trained to do, but lots of shareholders are actually interested in somet=
hing else. Sure they=E2=80=99ll take cash flows, cash flows are great, but =
they have other interests. Retail investors, for instance, seem to love mem=
es, and crypto, and Elon Musk. Big institutional investors tend to be inter=
ested in ESG risk, and more generally in the systemic risks of their portfo=
lios as a whole.One rough model that you could have for hedge fund activism=
 is that companies are always a bit behind the times in terms of knowing wh=
at shareholders want, and activists are in the business of reminding them, =
of pushing them to do what their shareholders want. For a long time, what s=
hareholders wanted was basically maximum earnings per share, and activists =
were in the business of telling corporate managers to buckle down and incre=
ase EPS.Now the market has evolved, shareholders want other things, and the=
re are activists to give it to them. We have talked about  a meme activist =
campaign=C2=A0pushing Macy=E2=80=99s Inc.=C2=A0to optimize its engagement w=
ith retail shareholders by putting out press releases about Teslas and cryp=
tocurrency. We have talked about a  diversified-investor activist campaign=
=C2=A0pushing Fox Corp. to enhance the value of its shareholders=E2=80=99 o=
verall portfolios by focusing on the profitability of=C2=A0other=C2=A0compa=
nies, not just Fox.And there are the ESG activists. Part of what the ESG ac=
tivists say is: =E2=80=9CIf you do better ESG things, that will increase yo=
ur cash flows in the long run,=E2=80=9D a traditional corporate-finance thi=
ng to say. But part of it is=C2=A0not=C2=A0that; part of it is just about a=
ppealing to more shareholders=E2=80=99 preferences in order to get a higher=
 valuation: =E2=80=9CIf you do better ESG things, more people will invest a=
nd the stock will go up even holding cash flows constant.=E2=80=9D ESG is w=
hat shareholders want, and activists are in the business of getting it for =
them.
 =20
   =20
      Facebook Meta Libra Diem Novi
   =20
 =20
I think the last time  we talked about Meta Platforms Inc.=E2=80=99s Diem s=
tablecoin project, it was Facebook Inc.=E2=80=99s Libra stablecoin project.=
 How times have changed. The dream of like =E2=80=9Cuse Facebook=E2=80=99s =
version of money to pay for stuff on Facebook=E2=80=9D probably made a bit=
=C2=A0less=C2=A0sense than =E2=80=9Cuse Meta=E2=80=99s version of money to =
pay for stuff in the metaverse,=E2=80=9D insofar as when you move into the =
metaverse you will need to pay for your virtual goods and services and you =
won=E2=80=99t be able to use paper money or probably even your credit card?=
 I don=E2=80=99t know, I am still hoping to go a few more months without kn=
owing what the metaverse is. But, sure, you=E2=80=99ll probably buy stuff i=
n it with crypto. That=C2=A0is not helping Diem much though:David Marcus, o=
ne of the top executives at Meta Platforms Inc. and the co-creator of the y=
et-to-be-launched=C2=A0Diem digital currency, is leaving the company after =
seven years to pursue other projects.=C2=A0Marcus, who joined the Facebook =
parent company in 2014 from PayPal Holdings Inc., ran the Messenger service=
 for years before moving over to form the company=E2=80=99s blockchain divi=
sion in 2018. He spent the last few years building Novi, the company=E2=80=
=99s digital wallet that launched in October, and co-founded Diem, a digita=
l currency formerly known as Libra that was intended as a way for people to=
 send money cross-border.Getting Diem off the ground has proven to be a str=
uggle for Meta and Marcus. Since the project was unveiled in 2019 =E2=80=94=
 with great fanfare and dozens of partners =E2=80=94 the currency=E2=80=99s=
 debut has been delayed and its original ambitions have been scaled back. D=
iem faced pushback from lawmakers and regulators when it was announced, and=
 while Meta is still a partner on the effort, Diem is now run independently=
.I will say that when Facebook announced Libra, I was embarrassingly bullis=
h on it? I thought something along the lines of: Well, anarchic decentraliz=
ed crypto has had a good run, but just as the anarchic decentralized intern=
et ended up the property of like four big companies, so crypto will end up =
just being a subsidiary of Facebook.  I said:You know =E2=80=A6 look at the=
 internet. In a real, true, important sense, the internet is decentralized =
and libertarian and empowering; the architecture of the internet is not con=
trolled by any government or corporation, and everyone can access and build=
 on it. But in another, also quite real, sense, the internet has been a pow=
erful tool for the centralizing of power. There are a zillion websites but =
you find them using Google; anyone can publish on the internet but you get =
your news from Facebook; anyone can sell anything on the internet but mostl=
y you buy stuff from Amazon; email is a free and open protocol but you use =
Gmail. The democratizing effect of the internet=E2=80=99s openness and dece=
ntralization is counteracted by its vast economies of scale and network eff=
ects, which tend to concentrate power in a few big winners.Basically the po=
int here is that if you replace the traditional social-regulatory technolog=
y of money creation with a new sort of=C2=A0computer=C2=A0technology of mon=
ey creation, odds are that the power of money creation will end up not so m=
uch in the hands of free-spirited individual hackers around the world, but =
in the hands of some giant tech company.=C2=A0In this case, Facebook Inc.I =
guess that could still happen, but it sure seems wrong now, doesn=E2=80=99t=
 it? I am not especially a crypto booster, and I think that a lot of the mu=
ch-hyped decentralized =E2=80=9CWeb3=E2=80=9D is just flimsy Ponzi schemes,=
 but it is interesting that so far crypto has been pretty resistant to take=
over by big tech companies.=C2=A0
 =20
   =20
      Excel influencing
   =20
 =20
Here is the story of Kat Norton, who worked as a securitization consultant =
until she =E2=80=9Cstarted going deep into inner work, work on myself: medi=
tation, mindfulness, manifestation,=E2=80=9D at which point she decided to =
be an Excel TikTok celebrity instead. Which is far more lucrative:By April,=
 I started rolling out a second course. I did my first six-figure month. Bu=
siness Insider had reached out for a feature. The whole Miss Excel project =
had been just scaling and growing. By June of 2021, I received the Microsof=
t MVP award. I also began working with Microsoft to learn more about their =
products so I could help my audience in better ways. The whole experience h=
as been just incredible. It scaled to my first six-figure day a couple of w=
eeks ago. I was super hyped about that.I used to work at an investment bank=
, though I never did the financial-modeling training that analysts get in t=
heir first weeks on the job. I gather that is normally taught by outside co=
nsultants. I think that if the analysts got their Excel training from peopl=
e who=C2=A0make more money in a day than the analysts will make in a year, =
they would all quit? =E2=80=9CIf I=E2=80=99m not launching courses, I work =
maybe 15 hours a week,=E2=80=9D Norton also says, which, I mean, if the ana=
lysts are not on a live deal they are working maybe 80 hours a week?=C2=A0
