background-color: #ccc;"> the theory anyway</a>.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">One criticism of this approach is that it actually=C2=A0<em>red=
uces=C2=A0</em>the influence that ESG-minded investors have over problemati=
c companies. If there is a company that does some coal mining, and also som=
e good environmental stuff, what you want is for the company to cut back on=
 the coal mining and ramp up the good stuff. If you own its stock, you can =
go meet with the managers and lobby for that approach. But if you have a br=
ight-line rule saying =E2=80=9Cno thermal coal,=E2=80=9D who will meet with=
 the managers and lobby for that approach?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
I think the answer is that a group of ESG activist investors have sprung up=
 whose basic mission is =E2=80=9Clobby companies to become more appealing t=
o ESG investors=E2=80=9D? <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
